# Commit Reminders

Proactively remind the user to commit. Don't let large amounts of work pile up
uncommitted (it did once — an entire feature phase sat unstaged for a day).

## When to remind

After finishing a meaningful unit of work, end the turn with a short reminder /
offer to commit. Trigger points:

- A feature or fix is complete and lint/build/tests pass.
- Right after a successful deploy (the deployed code should be committed too).
- Before starting a sizeable new piece of work, if there are already uncommitted
  changes.

Keep it to one line, e.g.: "This is a good checkpoint — want me to commit and
push?" Never commit without the user's explicit go-ahead.

## How to commit (when asked)

- Stage with `git add -A`, write a concise message (why over what), then push to
  `origin/main` (single-person project).
- Never commit secrets or build output. Verify `functions/node_modules`,
  `functions/lib`, `dist/`, and any real `.env*` keys stay out of the commit.
  (`.env.production` holding only `VITE_AI_PROVIDER=cloud` is fine.)
- Prefer smaller, focused commits over one giant batch.
